    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "could it be a nitrogen thing? i heard that can make them yellow. how do i fix the soil to make sure they get enough nitrogen? like what should the ph be?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, a nitrogen deficiency is a very strong possibility, as it directly causes the yellowing of older, lower leaves while the top growth remains green. To fix this, you can incorporate compost into the soil and apply a balanced fertilizer with a high nitrogen ratio, like 10-10-10, but be careful not to over-apply as too much nitrogen can burn the roots. For optimal uptake, your soil pH should ideally be between 6.0 and 6.8, as this range ensures the plant can easily access the nitrogen it needs. If the soil is already quite acidic, adding lime can help raise the pH into that sweet spot.",
